name: sample number

definition: A reference number relevant to the sample under study.

name: sample name

xrefs.description: The allowed value-type for this CV term.

definition: A reference string relevant to the sample under study.

name: sample state
definition: The chemical phase of a pure sample, or the state of a mixed sample.

xrefs.description: The allowed value-type for this CV term.

xrefs.description: The allowed value-type for this CV term.

xrefs.description: The allowed value-type for this CV term.

definition: Smallest mass difference between two equal magnitude peaks so that the valley between them is a specified fraction of the peak height.

name: resolution measurement method
definition: Which of the available standard measures is used to define whether two peaks are separate.

comment: This former purgatory term was made obsolete.
name: resolution type
definition: OBSOLETE Specify the nature of resolution for the mass analyzer. Resolution is usually either constant with respect to m/z or proportional to m/z.

name: accuracy

xrefs.description: The allowed value-type for this CV term.

definition: Accuracy is the degree of conformity of a measured mass to its actual value.

name: scan rate

xrefs.description: The allowed value-type for this CV term.

definition: Rate in Th/sec for scanning analyzers.

name: scan start time

xrefs.description: The allowed value-type for this CV term.

definition: The time that an analyzer started a scan, relative to the start of the MS run.

comment: OBSOLETE This former purgatory term was made obsolete.
name: Scan Function
definition: OBSOLETE Describes the type of mass analysis being performed. Two primary modes are: typical acquisition over a range of masses (Mass Scan), and Selected Ion Detection. The primary difference is that Selected Ion Detection produces a single value for the signal at the selected mass rather than producing a mass spectrum.

name: scan direction
definition: Direction in terms of m/z of the scan for scanning analyzers (low to high, or high to low).

name: scan law
definition: Describes the function in control of the m/z scan (for scanning instruments). Commonly the scan function is linear, but in principle any function can be used.

comment: OBSOLETE This former purgatory term was made obsolete.
name: scanning method
definition: Describes the acquisition data type produced by a tandem mass spectrometry experiment.

name: reflectron state

name: TOF Total Path Length

xrefs.description: The allowed value-type for this CV term.

definition: The length of the field free drift space in a time of flight mass spectrometer.

comment: This former purgatory term was made obsolete.
name: isolation width

xrefs.description: The allowed value-type for this CV term.

definition: OBSOLETE The total width (i.e. not half for plus-or-minus) of the gate applied around a selected precursor ion.

name: final MS exponent

xrefs.description: The allowed value-type for this CV term.

definition: Final MS level achieved when performing PFF with the ion trap (e.g. MS E10).

name: magnetic field strength

xrefs.description: The allowed value-type for this CV term.

definition: A property of space that produces a force on a charged particle equal to qv x B where q is the particle charge and v its velocity.

name: detector type
definition: Type of detector used in the mass spectrometer.

name: detector acquisition mode
definition: Method by which detector signal is acquired by the data system.

name: detector resolution

xrefs.description: The allowed value-type for this CV term.

definition: The resolving power of the detector to detect the smallest difference between two ions so that the valley between them is a specified fraction of the peak height.

name: sampling frequency

xrefs.description: The allowed value-type for this CV term.

definition: The rate of signal sampling (measurement) with respect to time.

name: deisotoping
definition: The removal of isotope peaks to represent the fragment ion as one data point and is commonly done to reduce complexity. It is done in conjunction with the charge state deconvolution.

name: charge deconvolution
definition: The determination of the mass of an ion based on the mass spectral peaks that represent multiple-charge ions.

name: peak picking
definition: Spectral peak processing conducted on the acquired data to convert profile data to centroided data.

name: m/z
definition: Three-character symbol m/z is used to denote the quantity formed by dividing the mass of an ion in unified atomic mass units by its charge number (regardless of sign). The symbol is written in italicized lower case letters with no spaces. Note 1: The term mass-to-charge-ratio is deprecated. Mass-to-charge ratio has been used for the abscissa of a mass spectrum, although the quantity measured is not the quotient of the ion's mass to its electric charge. The three-character symbol m/z is recommended for the quantity that is the independent variable in a mass spectrum Note 2: The proposed unit thomson (Th) is deprecated.

name: charge state

xrefs.description: The allowed value-type for this CV term.

definition: The charge state of the ion, single or multiple and positive or negatively charged.

name: peak intensity

xrefs.description: The allowed value-type for this CV term.

definition: Intensity of ions as measured by the height or area of a peak in a mass spectrum.

name: intensity unit
definition: Intensity units are commonly arbitrary. Detected in counts per second (cps) when using counting detectors, but measured in volts when using analog detectors.

name: dissociation method
definition: Fragmentation method used for dissociation or fragmentation.

name: collision energy

xrefs.description: The allowed value-type for this CV term.

definition: Energy for an ion experiencing collision with a stationary gas particle resulting in dissociation of the ion.

name: gaseous sample state
definition: State if the sample is in gaseous form.

name: liquid sample state
definition: State if the sample is in liquid form.

name: solid sample state

name: solution

name: suspension

name: chromatography
definition: OBSOLETE Chromatographic conditions used to obtain the sample.

name: continuous flow fast atom bombardment
definition: Fast atom bombardment ionization in which the analyte in solution is entrained in a flowing liquid matrix.

name: direct inlet
definition: The sample is directly inserted into the ion source, usually on the end of a heatable probe.

name: electrospray inlet
definition: Inlet used for introducing the liquid sample into an electrospray ionization source.

name: flow injection analysis
definition: Sample is directly injected or infused into the ionization source.

name: inductively coupled plasma
definition: A gas discharge ion source in which the energy to the plasma is supplied by electromagnetic induction.

name: infusion
definition: The continuous flow of solution of a sample into the ionization source.

name: jet separator
definition: A device that separates carrier gas from gaseous analyte molecules on the basis of diffusivity.

name: membrane separator
definition: A device to separate carrier molecules from analyte molecules on the basis of ease of diffusion across a semipermeable membrane.

name: moving belt
definition: Continuous moving surface in the form of a belt which passes through an ion source carrying analyte molecules.

name: moving wire
definition: Continuous moving surface in the form of a wire which passes through an ion source carrying analyte molecules.

name: open split
definition: A division of flowing stream of liquid into two streams.

name: particle beam
definition: Method for generating ions from a solution of an analyte.

name: reservoir
definition: A sample inlet method involving a reservoir.

name: septum
definition: A disc composed of a flexible material that seals the entrance to the reservoir. Can also be entrance to the vacuum chamber.

name: thermospray inlet
definition: A method for generating gas phase ions from a solution of an analyte by rapid heating of the sample.

name: atmospheric pressure chemical ionization
definition: Chemical ionization that takes place at atmospheric pressure as opposed to the reduced pressure is normally used for chemical ionization.

name: chemical ionization
definition: The formation of a new ion by the reaction of a neutral species with an ion. The process may involve transfer of an electron, a proton or other charged species between the reactants. When a positive ion results from chemical ionization the term may be used without qualification. When a negative ion results the term negative ion chemical ionization should be used. Note that this term is not synonymous with chemi-ionization.

comment: This term was made obsolete because it was replaced by electron ionization (MS:1000389).
name: Electronic Ionization
definition: OBSOLETE The ionization of an atom or molecule by electrons that are typically accelerated to energies between 50 and 150 eV. Usually 70 eV electrons are used to produce positive ions. The term 'electron impact' is not recommended.

name: electrospray ionization
definition: A process in which ionized species in the gas phase are produced from an analyte-containing solution via highly charged fine droplets, by means of spraying the solution from a narrow-bore needle tip at atmospheric pressure in the presence of a high electric field. When a pressurized gas is used to aid in the formation of a stable spray, the term pneumatically assisted electrospray ionization is used. The term ion spray is not recommended.

name: fast atom bombardment ionization
definition: The ionization of any species by the interaction of a focused beam of neutral atoms having a translational energy of several thousand eV with a sample that is typically dissolved in a solvent matrix. See also secondary ionization.

name: matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization
definition: The formation of gas-phase ions from molecules that are present in a solid or solvent matrix that is irradiated with a pulsed laser. See also laser desorption/ionization.

comment: This term was made obsolete because it was replaced by negative scan (MS:1000129).
name: negative ion mode
definition: OBSOLETE.

comment: This term was made obsolete because it was replaced by positive scan (MS:1000130).
name: positive ion mode
definition: OBSOLETE.

name: axial ejection linear ion trap
definition: A linear ion trap mass spectrometer where ions are ejected along the axis of the analyzer.

name: fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance mass spectrometer
definition: A mass spectrometer based on the principle of ion cyclotron resonance in which an ion in a magnetic field moves in a circular orbit at a frequency characteristic of its m/z value. Ions are coherently excited to a larger radius orbit using a pulse of radio frequency energy and their image charge is detected on receiver plates as a time domain signal. Fourier transformation of the time domain signal results in a frequency domain signal which is converted to a mass spectrum based in the inverse relationship between frequency and m/z.

name: magnetic sector
definition: A device that produces a magnetic field perpendicular to a charged particle beam that deflects the beam to an extent that is proportional to the particle momentum per unit charge. For a monoenergetic beam, the deflection is proportional to m/z.

name: quadrupole
definition: A mass spectrometer that consists of four parallel rods whose centers form the corners of a square and whose opposing poles are connected. The voltage applied to the rods is a superposition of a static potential and a sinusoidal radio frequency potential. The motion of an ion in the x and y dimensions is described by the Matthieu equation whose solutions show that ions in a particular m/z range can be transmitted along the z axis.

name: quadrupole ion trap
definition: Quadrupole Ion Trap mass analyzer captures the ions in a three dimensional ion trap and then selectively ejects them by varying the RF and DC potentials.

name: radial ejection linear ion trap
definition: A linear ion trap mass spectrometer where ions are ejected along the radius of the analyzer.

name: time-of-flight
definition: Instrument that separates ions by m/z in a field-free region after acceleration to a fixed acceleration energy.

name: baseline
definition: An attribute of resolution when recording the detector response in absence of the analyte.

name: full width at half-maximum
definition: A measure of resolution represented as width of the peak at half peak height.

name: ten percent valley
definition: An attribute of resolution when the ratio between adjacent signals is 10% of the signal height.

name: increasing m/z scan

name: channeltron
definition: A horn-shaped (or cone-shaped) continuous dynode particle multiplier. The ion strikes the inner surface of the device and induces the production of secondary electrons that in turn impinge on the inner surfaces to produce more secondary electrons. This avalanche effect produces an increase in signal in the final measured current pulse.

name: conversion dynode electron multiplier
definition: A surface that is held at high potential so that ions striking the surface produce electrons that are subsequently detected.

name: conversion dynode photomultiplier
definition: A detector in which ions strike a conversion dynode to produce electrons that in turn generate photons through a phosphorescent screen that are detected by a photomultiplier.

name: daly detector
definition: Detector consisting of a conversion dynode, scintillator and photomultiplier. The metal knob at high potential emits secondary electrons when ions impinge on the surface. The secondary electrons are accelerated onto the scintillator that produces light that is then detected by the photomultiplier detector.

name: electron multiplier tube
definition: A device to amplify the current of a beam or packet of charged particles or photons by incidence upon the surface of an electrode to produce secondary electrons.

name: faraday cup
definition: A conducting cup or chamber that intercepts a charged particle beam and is electrically connected to a current measuring device.

name: focal plane array
definition: An array of detectors for spatially disperse ion beams in which all ions simultaneously impinge on the detector plane.

name: microchannel plate detector
definition: A thin plate that contains a closely spaced array of channels that each act as a continuous dynode particle multiplier. A charged particle, fast neutral particle, or photon striking the plate causes a cascade of secondary electrons that ultimately exits the opposite side of the plate.

name: multi-collector
definition: A detector system commonly used in inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometers.

name: photomultiplier
definition: A detector for conversion of the ion/electron signal into photon(s) which are then amplified and detected.

name: analog-digital converter
definition: Analog-to-digital converter (abbreviated ADC, A/D or A to D) is an electronic integrated circuit (i/c) that converts continuous signals to discrete digital numbers.

name: pulse counting

name: time-digital converter

name: transient recorder

name: profile spectrum

name: collision-induced dissociation
definition: The dissociation of an ion after collisional excitation. The term collisional-activated dissociation is not recommended.

name: plasma desorption
definition: The ionization of material in a solid sample by bombarding it with ionic or neutral atoms formed as a result of the fission of a suitable nuclide, typically 252Cf. Synonymous with fission fragment ionization.

name: post-source decay
definition: A technique specific to reflectron time-of-flight mass spectrometers where product ions of metastable transitions or collision-induced dissociations generated in the drift tube prior to entering the reflectron are m/z separated to yield product ion spectra.

name: surface-induced dissociation
definition: Fragmentation that results from the collision of an ion with a surface.

definition: OBSOLETE Odd-electron ions may dissociate to form either odd or even-electron ions, whereas even-electron ions generally form even-electron fragment ions.

name: peak
definition: A localized region of relatively large ion signal in a mass spectrum. Although peaks are often associated with particular ions, the terms peak and ion should not be used interchangeably.

name: total ion current chromatogram
definition: Chromatogram obtained by plotting the total ion current detected in each of a series of mass spectra recorded as a function of retention time.

name: unified atomic mass unit

name: accelerator mass spectrometry
definition: OBSOLETE A mass spectrometry technique in which atoms extracted from a sample are ionized, accelerated to MeV energies and separated according to their momentum, charge and energy.

name: atmospheric pressure matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization
definition: Matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization in which the sample target is at atmospheric pressure and the ions formed by the pulsed laser are sampled through a small aperture into the mass spectrometer.

name: atmospheric pressure ionization
definition: Any ionization process in which ions are formed in the gas phase at atmospheric pressure.

comment: This term was made obsolete because it was replaced by atmospheric pressure photoionization (MS:1000382).
name: Atmostpheric Pressure Photoionization
definition: OBSOLETE Atmospheric pressure chemical ionization in which the reactant ions are generated by photo-ionization.

name: blackbody infrared radiative dissociation
definition: A special case of infrared multiphoton dissociation wherein excitation of the reactant ion is caused by absorption of infrared photons radiating from heated blackbody surroundings, which are usually the walls of a vacuum chamber. See also infrared multiphoton dissociation.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term ion reaction was made obsolete.
name: charge-remote fragmentation
definition: OBSOLETE A fragmentation of an even-electron ion in which the cleaved bond is not adjacent to the apparent charge site.

comment: This former purgatory term was made obsolete.
name: consecutive reaction monitoring
definition: OBSOLETE MSn experiment with three or more stages of m/z separation and in which a particular multi-step reaction path is monitored.

name: charge stripping
definition: The reaction of a positive ion with an atom or molecule that results in the removal of one or more electrons from the ion.

name: delayed extraction
definition: The application of the accelerating voltage pulse after a time delay in desorption ionization from a surface. The extraction delay can produce energy focusing in a time-of-flight mass spectrometer.

name: desorption ionization
definition: The formation of ions from a solid or liquid material after the rapid vaporization of that sample.

name: direct insertion probe
definition: A device for introducing a solid or liquid sample into a mass spectrometer ion source for desorption ionization.

name: direct liquid introduction
definition: The delivery of a liquid sample into a mass spectrometer for spray or desorption ionization.

name: electron capture dissociation
definition: A process in which a multiply protonated molecules interacts with a low energy electrons. Capture of the electron leads the liberation of energy and a reduction in charge state of the ion with the production of the (M + nH) (n-1)+ odd electron ion, which readily fragments.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term ion chemical type was made obsolete.
name: even-electron ion
definition: OBSOLETE An ion containing no unpaired electrons in its ground electronic state, e.g. CH3+ in its ground state.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term ion reaction was made obsolete.
name: electron-induced excitation in organics
definition: OBSOLETE The reaction of an ion with an electron in which the translational energy of the collision is converted into internal energy of the ion.

name: electron multiplier
definition: A device to amplify the current of a beam or packet of charged particles or photons by incidence upon the surface of an electrode to produce secondary electrons. The secondary electrons are then accelerated to other electrodes or parts of a continuous electrode to produce further secondary electrons.

name: electrostatic energy analyzer
definition: A device consisting of conducting parallel plates, concentric cylinders or concentric spheres that separates charged particles according to their kinetic energy by means of an electric field that is constant in time.

name: flowing afterglow
definition: An ion source immersed in a flow of helium or other inert buffer gas that carries the ions through a meter-long reactor at pressures around 100 Pa.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term mass spectrometer was made obsolete.
name: high-field asymmetric waveform ion mobility spectrometry
definition: OBSOLETE The separation of ions between two concentric cylindrical electrodes due to application of a high voltage asymmetric waveform whereby ions migrate towards one of the two electrodes depending on the ratio of the high- to low-field mobility of the ion.

name: field desorption
definition: The formation of gas-phase ions from a material deposited on a solid surface in the presence of a high electric field. Because this process may encompass ionization by field ionization or other mechanisms, it is not recommended as a synonym for field desorption ionization.

name: field ionization
definition: The removal of electrons from any species by interaction with a high electric field.

name: glow discharge ionization
definition: The formation of ions in the gas phase and from solid samples at the cathode by application of a voltage to a low pressure gas.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term mass spectrometer was made obsolete.
name: ion kinetic energy spectrometry
definition: OBSOLETE A method of analysis in which a beam of ions is separated according to the ratio of its translational energy to charge.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term mass spectrometer was made obsolete.
name: ion mobility spectrometry
definition: OBSOLETE The separation of ions according to their velocity through a buffer gas under the influence of an electric field.

name: infrared multiphoton dissociation
definition: Multiphoton ionization where the reactant ion dissociates as a result of the absorption of multiple infrared photons.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term mass spectrometry was made obsolete.
name: isotope ratio mass spectrometry
definition: OBSOLETE The measurement of the relative quantity of the different isotopes of an element in a material with a mass spectrometer.

name: ion trap
definition: A device for spatially confining ions using electric and magnetic fields alone or in combination.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term ion reaction was made obsolete.
name: kinetic energy release distribution
definition: OBSOLETE Distribution of values of translational kinetic energy release for an ensemble of metastable ions undergoing a specific dissociation reaction.

comment: This term was made obsolete because it was replaced by laser desorption ionization (MS:1000393).
name: Laser Desorption
definition: OBSOLETE The formation of ions through the interaction of a laser with a material or with gas-phase ions or molecules.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term mass spectrometer was made obsolete.
name: mass analyzed ion kinetic energy spectrometry
definition: OBSOLETE Spectra that are obtained from a sector mass spectrometer that incorporates at least one magnetic sector plus one electric sector in reverse geometry. The accelerating voltage, V, and the magnetic sector field, B, are set at fixed values to select the precursor ions, which are then allowed to dissociate or to react in a field free region between the two sectors. The kinetic energy product ions of m/z selected precursor ions is analyzed by scanning the electric sector field, E. The width of the product ion spectrum peaks is related to the kinetic energy release distribution (KERD) for the dissociation process.

comment: This former purgatory term was made obsolete.
name: mass spectrometry
definition: OBSOLETE The branch of science that deals with all aspects of mass spectrometers and the results obtained with these instruments.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term mass spectrometer was made obsolete.
name: mass spectrometry/mass spectrometry
definition: OBSOLETE The acquisition, study and spectra of the electrically charged products or precursors of a m/z selected ion or ions.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term m/z Separation Method was made obsolete.
name: multiple stage mass spectrometry
definition: OBSOLETE Multiple stages of precursor ion m/z selection followed by product ion detection for successive progeny ions.

name: Negative Ion chemical ionization
definition: Chemical ionization that results in the formation of negative ions.

name: neutralization reionization mass spectrometry
definition: With this technique, m/z selected ions form neutrals by charge transfer to a collision gas or by dissociation. The neutrals are separated from the remaining ions and ionized in collisions with a second gas. This method is used to investigate reaction intermediates and other unstable species.

name: photoionization
definition: The ionization of an atom or molecule by a photon, written M + h? ? M^+ + e. The term photon impact is not recommended.

name: pyrolysis mass spectrometry
definition: A mass spectrometry technique in which the sample is heated to the point of decomposition and the gaseous decomposition products are introduced into the ion source.

name: collision quadrupole
definition: A transmission quadrupole to which an oscillating potential is applied so as to focus a beam of ions through a collision gas with no m/z separation.

name: resonance enhanced multiphoton ionization
definition: Multiphoton ionization in which the ionization cross section is significantly enhanced because the energy of the incident photons is resonant with an intermediate excited state of the neutral species.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term mass spectrometer was made obsolete.
name: residual gas analyzer
definition: OBSOLETE A mass spectrometer used to measure the composition and pressure of gasses in an evacuated chamber.

name: surface enhanced laser desorption ionization
definition: The formation of ionized species in the gas phase from analytes deposited on a particular surface substrate which is irradiated with a laser beam of which wavelength is absorbed by the surface. See also desorption/ionization on silicon and laser desorption/ionization.

name: surface enhanced neat desorption
definition: Matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization in which the matrix is covalently linked to the target surface.

comment: This term was made obsolete because it was replaced by surface ionization (MS:1000406).
name: suface ionization
definition: OBSOLETE The ionization of a neutral species when it interacts with a solid surface with an appropriate work function and temperature.

name: selected ion flow tube
definition: A device in which m/z selected ions are entrained in an inert carrier gas and undergo ion-molecule reactions.

name: sustained off-resonance irradiation
definition: A technique associated with Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance (FT-ICR) mass spectrometry to carry out ion/neutral reactions such as low-energy collision-induced dissociation. A radio-frequency electric field of slightly off-resonance to the cyclotron frequency of the reactant ion cyclically accelerates and decelerates the reactant ion that is confined in the Penning ion trap. The ion's orbit does not exceed the dimensions of ion trap while the ion undergoes an ion/neutral species process that produces a high average translational energy for an extended time.

comment: This term was made obsolete because it was replaced by spark ionization (MS:1000404).
name: Spark Source Mass Spectrometry
definition: OBSOLETE Mass spectrometry using spark ionization.

name: stored waveform inverse fourier transform
definition: A technique to create excitation waveforms for ions in FT-ICR mass spectrometer or Paul ion trap. An excitation waveform in the time-domain is generated by taking the inverse Fourier transform of an appropriate frequency-domain programmed excitation spectrum, in which the resonance frequencies of ions to be excited are included. This technique may be used for selection of precursor ions in MS2 experiments.

name: total ion current

xrefs.description: The allowed value-type for this CV term.

definition: The sum of all the separate ion currents carried by the ions of different m/z contributing to a complete mass spectrum or in a specified m/z range of a mass spectrum.

name: time lag focusing
definition: Energy focusing in a time-of-flight mass spectrometer that is accomplished by introducing a time delay between the formation of the ions and the application of the accelerating voltage pulse.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term mass spectrometer was made obsolete.
name: time-of-flight mass spectrometer
definition: OBSOLETE An instrument that separates ions by m/z in a field-free region after acceleration to a fixed kinetic energy.

name: cyclotron
definition: A device that uses an oscillating electric field and magnetic field to accelerate charged particles.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term mass spectrometer was made obsolete.
name: double-focusing mass spectrometer
definition: OBSOLETE A mass spectrometer that uses a magnetic sector for m/z focusing and an electric sector for energy focusing of an ion beam.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term mass spectrometer was made obsolete.
name: hybrid mass spectrometer
definition: OBSOLETE A mass spectrometer that combines m/z analyzers of different types to perform tandem mass spectrometry.

name: linear ion trap
definition: A two dimensional Paul ion trap in which ions are confined in the axial dimension by means of an electric field at the ends of the trap.

comment: This former purgatory term was made obsolete.
name: mass spectrograph obsolete
definition: OBSOLETE An instrument that separates a beam of ions according to their mass-to-charge ratio in which the ions are directed onto a focal plane detector such as a photographic plate.

comment: This former purgatory term was made obsolete.
name: mass spectrometer
definition: OBSOLETE An instrument that measures the mass-to-charge ratio and relative abundances of ions.

name: mass spectrum
definition: A plot of the relative abundance of a beam or other collection of ions as a function of the mass-to-charge ratio (m/z).

comment: This former purgatory term was made obsolete.
name: mattauch-herzog geometry
definition: OBSOLETE An arrangement for a double-focusing mass spectrometer in which a deflection of ?/(4 ?(2)) radians in a radial electric field is followed by a magnetic deflection of ?/2 radians.

comment: This former purgatory term was made obsolete.
name: nier-johnson geometry
definition: OBSOLETE An arrangement for a double-focusing mass spectrometer in which a deflection of ?/2 radians in a radial electric field analyzer is followed by a magnetic deflection of ?/3 radians.

comment: This term was made obsolete because it is redundant to quadrupole ion trap.
name: paul ion trap
definition: OBSOLETE A device that permits the trapping of ions by means of an alternating current voltage. The ejection of ions with a m/z less than a prescribed value and retention of those with higher mass depends on the application of radio frequency voltages between a ring electrode and two end-cap electrodes to confine the ions in a circular path. The choice of these voltages determines the m/z below which ions are ejected.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term mass spectrometer was made obsolete.
name: prolate traochoidal mass spectrometer
definition: OBSOLETE A mass spectrometer in which the ions of different m/z are separated by means of crossed electric and magnetic fields in such a way that the selected ions follow a prolate trochoidal path.

comment: This former purgatory term was made obsolete.
name: quistor
definition: OBSOLETE An abbreviation of quadrupole ion storage trap. This term is synonymous with Paul Ion Trap. If so then add a synonym to paul and obsolete this term.

name: reflectron
definition: A time-of-flight mass spectrometer that uses a static electric field to reverse the direction of travel of the ions entering it. A reflectron improves mass resolution by assuring that ions of the same m/z but different kinetic energy arrive at the detector at the same time.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term mass spectrometer was made obsolete.
name: sector mass spectrometer
definition: OBSOLETE A mass spectrometer consisting of one or more magnetic sectors for m/z selection in a beam of ions. Such instruments may also have one or more electric sectors for energy selection.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term mass spectrometer was made obsolete.
name: tandem mass spectrometer
definition: OBSOLETE A mass spectrometer designed for mass spectrometry/mass spectrometry.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term mass spectrometer was made obsolete.
name: transmission quadrupole mass spectrometer
definition: OBSOLETE A mass spectrometer that consists of four parallel rods whose centers form the corners of a square and whose opposing poles are connected. The voltage applied to the rods is a superposition of a static potential and a sinusoidal radio frequency potential. The motion of an ion in the x and y dimensions is described by the Matthieu equation whose solutions show that ions in a particular m/z range can be transmitted along the z axis.

name: accelerating voltage

xrefs.description: The allowed value-type for this CV term.

definition: The electrical potential used to impart kinetic energy to ions in a mass spectrometer.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term m/z Separation Method was made obsolete.
name: cyclotron motion
definition: OBSOLETE The circular motion of a charged particle moving at velocity v in a magnetic field B that results from the force qvB.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term mass spectrometer was made obsolete.
name: dynamic mass spectrometry
definition: OBSOLETE A mass spectrometer in which m/z separation using one or more electric fields that vary with time.

name: einzel lens
definition: Three element charged particle lens in which the first and third elements are held at the same voltage. Such a lens produces focusing without changing the translational energy of the particle.

name: electric field strength

xrefs.description: The allowed value-type for this CV term.

definition: The magnitude of the force per unit charge at a given point in space.

name: first stability region
definition: The region of a Mathieu stability diagram closest to the origin. Ions within this region can traverse the full length of a transmission quadrupole.

name: fringing field
definition: The electric or magnetic field that extends from the edge of a sector, lens or other ion optics element.

name: kinetic energy analyzer
definition: A device for measuring the kinetic energy of charged particles using a retarding field, time-of-flight, or the extent of deflection in an electric or magnetic field.

comment: This former purgatory term was made obsolete.
name: mass limit
definition: OBSOLETE The m/z value above which ions cannot be detected in a mass spectrometer.

comment: This former purgatory term was made obsolete.
name: scan m/z range?
definition: OBSOLETE The limit of m/z over which a mass spectrometer can detect ions.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term m/z Separation Method was made obsolete.
name: mass selective axial ejection
definition: OBSOLETE The use of mass selective instability to eject ions of selected m/z values from an ion trap.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term m/z Separation Method was made obsolete.
name: mass selective instability
definition: OBSOLETE A method for selective ejection of ions according to their m/z value in an ion trap.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term m/z Separation Method was made obsolete.
name: mathieu stability diagram
definition: OBSOLETE A graphical representation expressed in terms of reduced coordinates that describes charged particle motion in a quadrupole mass filter or quadrupole ion trap mass spectrometer.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term m/z Separation Method was made obsolete.
name: orthogonal extraction
definition: OBSOLETE The pulsed acceleration of ions perpendicular to their direction of travel into a time-of-flight mass spectrometer. Ions may be extracted from a directional ion source, drift tube or m/z separation stage.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term m/z Separation Method was made obsolete.
name: resonance ion ejection
definition: OBSOLETE A mode of ion ejection in a quadrupole ion trap that relies on a auxiliary radio frequency voltage that is applied to the end-cap electrodes. The voltage is tuned to the secular frequency of a particular ion to eject it.

name: space charge effect
definition: The mutual repulsion of particles of like charge that limits the current in a charged-particle beam and causes beams or packets of charged particles to expand radially over time.

name: static field
definition: An electric or magnetic field that does not change in time.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term m/z Separation Method was made obsolete.
name: 2E Mass Spectrum
definition: OBSOLETE A mass spectrum obtained by setting the electric sector field E to twice the value required to transmit the main ion-beam thereby allowing ions with a kinetic energy-to-charge ratio twice that of the main ion-beam to be transmitted. Product ions resulting from partial charge transfer reactions such as m^2+ + N ? m^+ + N^+ that occur in a collision cell (containing a gas, N) located in a field-free region preceding a magnetic and electric sector combination are detected. When the magnetic sector field B is scanned, a mass spectrum of singly charged product ions of doubly charged precursor ions is obtained.

name: charge inversion mass spectrum
definition: The measurement of the relative abundance of ions that result from a charge inversion reaction as a function of m/z.

comment: This former purgatory term was made obsolete.
name: constant neutral loss scan
definition: OBSOLETE Spectrum of all precursor ions that undergo a selected m/z decrement.

comment: This former purgatory term was made obsolete.
name: constant neutral gain scan
definition: OBSOLETE Spectrum of all precursor ions that undergo a selected m/z increment.

name: constant neutral gain spectrum
definition: A spectrum formed of all product ions that have been produced by gain of a pre-selected neutral mass following the reaction with and addition of the gas in a collision cell.

name: constant neutral loss spectrum
definition: A spectrum formed of all product ions that have been produced with a selected m/z decrement from any precursor ions. The spectrum shown correlates to the precursor ion spectrum. See also neutral loss spectrum.

comment: This term was made obsolete because it was replaced by consecutive reaction monitoring (MS:1000244).
name: consecutive reaction monitoring
definition: OBSOLETE A type of MS2 experiments with three or more stages of m/z separation and in which a particular multi-step reaction path is monitored.

name: e/2 mass spectrum
definition: A mass spectrum obtained using a sector mass spectrometer in which the electric sector field E is set to half the value required to transmit the main ion-beam. This spectrum records the signal from doubly charged product ions of charge-stripping reactions.

comment: This former purgatory term was made obsolete.
name: linked scan
definition: OBSOLETE A scan in an instrument with two or more m/z analysers or in a sector mass spectrometer that incorporates at least one magnetic sector and one electric sector. Two or more of the analyzers are scanned simultaneously so as to preserve a predetermined relationship between scan parameters to produce a product ion, precursor ion or constant neutral loss spectrum.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term linked scan was made obsolete.
name: linked scan at constant b/e
definition: OBSOLETE A linked scan at constant B/E may be performed on a sector mass spectrometer that incorporates at least one magnetic sector plus one electric sector. The magnetic field B and the electric field E are scanned simultaneously while the accelerating voltage V is held constant, so as to maintain the ratio of the two fields constant. This linked scan may record a product ion spectrum of dissociation or other reactions occurring in a field free region preceding the two sectors.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term linked scan was made obsolete.
name: Linked Scan at Constant E2/V
definition: OBSOLETE A linked scan performed on a sector instrument that incorporates at least one electric sector plus one magnetic sector. The electric sector field, E, and the accelerating voltage, V, are scanned simultaneously, so as to maintain the ratio E2/V at a constant value. This linked scan recordss a product ion spectrum of dissociation or other reactions occurring in a field free region (FFR) preceding the two sectors.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term linked scan was made obsolete.
name: Linked Scan at Constant B2/E
definition: OBSOLETE A linked scan performed on a sector mass spectrometer that incorporates at least one electric sector plus one magnetic sector in either order. The accelerating voltage is fixed and the magnetic field, B, and the electric field, E, are scanned simultaneously so as to maintain the ratio B2/E at a constant value. This linked scan records a precursor ion spectrum of dissociation or other reactions occurring in the field free region preceding the two sectors. The term B2/E linked scan is not recommended.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term linked scan was made obsolete.
name: Linked Scan at Constant B[1-(E/E0)]^1/2 / E
definition: OBSOLETE A linked scan performed on a sector instrument that incorporates at least one electric sector plus one magnetic sector placed in either order. The accelerating voltage is fixed while scanning the magnetic field, B, and electric field, E, simultaneously, so as to maintain the quantity B[1-(E/E0)]1/2/E at a constant value. This linked scan records a constant neutral mass loss (or gain) spectrum of dissociation or other reactions occurring in a field free region preceding the two sectors. E0 is the electric field required to transmit the singly charged analog of the desired neutral fragment. The term B[1-(E/E0)]1/2/E linked scan.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term m/z Separation Method was made obsolete.
name: MS/MS in Time
definition: OBSOLETE A tandem mass spectrometry method in which product ion spectra are recorded in a single m/z analyzer (such as a Paul Ion Trap or FTMS) in discreet steps over time. Ions in a specific m/z range are selected, dissociated, and the product ions analyzed sequentially in time.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term m/z Separation Method was made obsolete.
name: MS/MS in Space
definition: OBSOLETE A tandem mass spectrometry method in which product ion spectra are recorded in m/z analyzers separated in space. Specific m/z separation functions are designed such that in one section of the instrument ions are selected, dissociated in an intermediate region, and the product ions are then transmitted to another analyser for m/z separation and data acquisition.

name: neutral loss
definition: The loss of an uncharged species during a rearrangement process.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term product ion was made obsolete.
name: nth generation product ion
definition: OBSOLETE Serial product ions from dissociation of selected precursor ions where n refers to the number of stages of dissociation. The term granddaughter ion is deprecated.

comment: This former purgatory term was made obsolete.
name: nth generation product ion scan
definition: OBSOLETE The specific scan functions or processes that record the appropriate generation of product ion or ions of any m/z selected precursor ions.

comment: This term was made obsolete because it was merged with MSn spectrum (MS:1000580).
name: nth generation product ion spectrum
definition: OBSOLETE The mass spectrum recorded from any mass spectrometer in which the appropriate scan function can be set to record the appropriate generation product ion or ions of m/z selected precursor ions.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term ion role was made obsolete.
name: precursor ion
definition: OBSOLETE An ion that reacts to form particular product ions. The reaction can be unimolecular dissociation, ion/molecule reaction, isomerization, or change in charge state. The term parent ion is deprecated.

name: precursor ion spectrum
definition: Spectrum generated by scanning precursor m/z while monitoring a fixed product m/z.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term ion role was made obsolete.
name: product ion
definition: OBSOLETE An ion formed as the product of a reaction involving a particular precursor ion. The reaction can be unimolecular dissociation to form fragment ions, an ion/molecule reaction, or simply involve a change in the number of charges. The term fragment ion is deprecated. The term daughter ion is deprecated.

comment: This term was made obsolete because it was merged with MSn spectrum (MS:1000580).
name: product ion spectrum
definition: OBSOLETE A mass spectrum recorded from any spectrometer in which the appropriate m/z separation scan function is set to record the product ion or ions of selected precursor ions.

comment: This child of the former purgatory term ion chemical type was made obsolete.
name: progeny ion
definition: OBSOLETE A charged product of a series of consecutive reactions that includes product ions, 1st generation product ions, 2nd generation product ions, etc. Given the sequential fragmentation scheme: M1+ -> M2+ -> M3+ -> M4+ -> M5+. M4+ is the precursor ion of M5+, a 1st generation product ion of M3+, a 2nd generation product ion of M2+ and a 3rd generation product ion of M1+.

name: array detector
definition: Detector comprising several ion collection elements, arranged in a line or grid where each element is an individual detector.

name: conversion dynode
definition: A surface that is held at high potential such that ions striking the surface produce electrons that are subsequently detected.

name: dynode
definition: One of a series of electrodes in a photomultiplier tube. Such an arrangement is able to amplify the current emitted by the photocathode.

name: focal plane collector
definition: A detector for spatially disperse ion beams in which all ions simultaneously impinge on the detector plane.

name: ion-to-photon detector
definition: A detector in which ions strike a conversion dynode to produce electrons that in turn strike a phosphor and the resulting photons are detected by a photomultiplier.

name: point collector
definition: A detector in which the ion beam is focused onto a point and the individual ions arrive sequentially.

name: postacceleration detector
definition: A detector in which the charged particles are accelerated to a high velocity and impinge on a conversion dynode, emitting secondary electrons. The electrons are accelerated onto a phosphor screen, which emits photons that are in turn detected using a photomultiplier or other photon detector.

name: adiabatic ionization
definition: A process whereby an electron is removed from an atom, ion, or molecule to produce an ion in its lowest energy state.

name: associative ionization

name: atmospheric pressure photoionization
definition: Atmospheric pressure chemical ionization in which the reactant ions are generated by photo-ionization.

name: autodetachment
definition: The formation of a neutral when a negative ion in a discrete state with an energy greater than the detachment threshold loses an electron spontaneously without further interaction with an energy source.

name: autoionization
definition: The formation of an ion when an atom or molecule in a discrete state with an energy greater than the ionization threshold loses an electron spontaneously without further interaction with an energy source.

name: charge exchange ionization
definition: The interaction of an ion with an atom or molecule in which the charge on the ion is transferred to the neutral without the dissociation of either. Synonymous with charge transfer ionization.

name: chemi-ionization

name: desorption/ionization on silicon
definition: The formation of ions by laser desorption ionization of a sample deposited on a porous silicon surface.

name: dissociative ionization
definition: The reaction of a gas-phase molecule that results in its decomposition to form products, one of which is an ion.

name: electron ionization
definition: The ionization of an atom or molecule by electrons that are typically accelerated to energies between 50 and 150 eV. Usually 70 eV electrons are used to produce positive ions. The term 'electron impact' is not recommended.

name: membrane inlet

name: microelectrospray

name: nanoelectrospray
definition: Electrospray ionization at a flow rate less than ~25 nL/min. Nanoelectrospray is synonymous with nanospray. The flow is dependent on the potenial on the tip of the electrospray needle and/or a gas presure to push the sample through the needle. See also electrospray ionization and microelectrospray.

name: penning ionization
definition: Ionization that occurs through the interaction of two or more neutral gaseous species, at least one of which is internally excited.

name: plasma desorption ionization

name: soft ionization

name: spark ionization

name: surface-assisted laser desorption ionization

name: surface ionization

name: thermal ionization

name: vertical ionization

name: MSn spectrum
definition: MSn refers to multi-stage MS2 experiments designed to record product ion spectra where n is the number of product ion stages (progeny ions). For ion traps, sequential MS/MS experiments can be undertaken where n > 2 whereas for a simple triple quadrupole system n=2. Use the term ms level (MS:1000511) for specifying n.

name: SRM spectrum
definition: Spectrum obtained when data are acquired from specific product ions corresponding to m/z values of selected precursor ions a recorded via two or more stages of mass spectrometry. The precursor/product ion pair is called a transition pair. Data can be obtained for a single transition pair or multiple transition pairs. Multiple time segments of different transition pairs can exist in a single file. Single precursor ions can have multiple product ions consitituting multiple transition pairs. Selected reaction monitoring can be performed as tandem mass spectrometry in time or tandem mass spectrometry in space.

name: Savitzky-Golay smoothing
definition: Reduces intensity spikes by applying local polynomial regression (of degree k) on a distribution (of at least k+1 equally spaced points) to determine the smoothed value for each point. It tends to preserve features of the distribution such as relative maxima, minima and width, which are usually 'flattened' by other adjacent averaging techniques.

name: LOWESS smoothing
definition: Reduces intensity spikes by applying a modelling method known as locally weighted polynomial regression. At each point in the data set a low-degree polynomial is fit to a subset of the data, with explanatory variable values near the point whose response is being estimated. The polynomial is fit using weighted least squares, giving more weight to points near the point whose response is being estimated and less weight to points further away. The value of the regression function for the point is then obtained by evaluating the local polynomial using the explanatory variable values for that data point. The LOESS fit is complete after regression function values have been computed for each of the n data points. Many of the details of this method, such as the degree of the polynomial model and the weights, are flexible.

name: Gaussian smoothing
definition: Reduces intensity spikes by convolving the data with a one-dimensional Gaussian function.

name: moving average smoothing
definition: Reduces intensity spikes by averaging each point with two or more adjacent points. The more adjacent points that used, the stronger the smoothing effect.
